<section id="history" class="post-section">
    <header class="post-header">
        <h2>History</h2>
    </header>
    <div>
        <figure class="float-right">
            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d0/Reconstruction_of_the_Signing_of_the_Treaty_of_Waitangi%2C_Marcus_King_%2816044258961%29.jpg" alt="The signing of te tiriti o Waitangi">
            <figcaption>The signing of te Tiriti o Waitangi<br><i>Image: <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Reconstruction_of_the_Signing_of_the_Treaty_of_Waitangi,_Marcus_King_(16044258961).jpg">Archives New Zealand</a>, <a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.0">CC BY-SA 2.0</a>, via Wikimedia Commons</i></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>In 1840, more than 500 Māori rangatira signed <i>te Tiriti o Waitangi</i> (The Treaty of Waitangi), an agreement between tangata whenua and the British crown. There are two versions of the treaty, one in English and one in te reo Māori, which means there are some not insignificant differences with the phrasing and language used.</p>
        <p>To simplify years of work by experts on how interperet this document, the European version said that the Crown would get sovereignty over the land, ‘exclusive and undisturbed possession' of Māori land, while the te reo Māori version says that the crown would get governance over the land, and that Māori would be guaranteed tino rangatiratanga - full rights of chieftainship over their whenua and taonga. It is worth mentioning that the vast majority of Māori who signed the treaty signed the te reo version.</p>
        <p>This resulted in years of conflict, land being stolen, erasure of Māori culture, and other acts of colonisation by Pākehā. In 1854, Aotearoa New Zealand adopted the British system of democracy, and until 1867, Māori could only vote if they were men who were the sole owners of land. This resulted in many Māori, who didn't own their land outright, not being able to vote. This was changed in 1867, with the creation of four <i>Māori electorates</i> (out of 70 seats total), and all Māori men could vote.</p>
    </div>
</section>
